rComments: Lectures were 95% textbook based, with 2 guest lectures being worth almost 10% of the final exam (over 4% of final grade). Cares too much about "formal method of answering questions" - can lose 20% of test mark off sloppiness. Follow rubric of lab reports and you will do well.

Honestly her lectures are textbook 2.0, but worse, because she has to cover vast amount of topic in 1 hour time frame. She talks about her research projects in a manner that makes her feel superior Study tip if you get this prof: don't go to lectures, but rather read and make notes based on textbook. You'll still be able to pull a high 70s or 80s

Professor Aimy opened my eyes to the world of heat and mass transfer and the importance of formatting. I understand that as an engineer, the font size and spacing of my reports is more important than the actual material covered. Her random tidbits of information and guest lectures truly made me have a better understanding of the subject matter.

Her marking scheme is the most flawed and outdated system there is. The material is marked as if it was submitted to an English essay writing class, focused on formatting and literally font size and type, while the actual content of the report is completely ignored.

Lectures are a complete waste of time. She babbles on in class about her collaborations with past students and the projects they worked on. in the last 15  minutes of class she will attempt to copy out a question from the book only to make several mistakes and email out a correction to her students 3 days later. Just read the book on your own.
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Get ready to read', 'Tough grader']
